         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">23/9/76 ¶  ¶ I have to thank you, dear Dr Hooker, for the presentation copy of your Primery Botany. ¶  It is an excellent work for beginners, and it is a wonder, that you could find time even for effo...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.09.23a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 184.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS black-edged: M's brother-in-law, Eduard Wehl, died on 11 February 1876.</p>
               </note>23/9/76</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have to thank you, dear Dr Hooker, for the presentation copy of your Primery Botany.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1876a). The copy is no longer in the library at the Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
               </note> It is an excellent work for beginners, and it is a wonder, that you could find time even for efforts in this direction</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">In my School-flora the <name key="Plumbagineae">Plumbagineae</name> will take a place next to the <name key="Frankeniaceae">Frankeniaceae</name>; and the <name key="Plantagineae">Plantagineae</name> next to the <name key="Loganiaceae">Loganiaceae</name>. I find no difficulty to dispose of the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> among <name key="Thalamiflorae">Thalamiflorae</name> &amp; <name key="Calyciflorae">Calyciflorae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <name key="Plumbagineae">Plumbagineae</name> followed <name key="Frankeniaceae">Frankeniaceae</name> in B79.06.04; the second part of that work, which would have contained <name key="Plantagineae">Plantagineae</name> and <name key="Loganiaceae">Loganiaceae</name>, was never published. In his other systematic listings, e.g., B86.04.05 and B89.12.03, M followed the scheme proposed here. In Bentham (1863-78), <name key="Plantagineae">Plantagineae</name> followed the Labiateae and <name key="Plumbagineae">Plumbagineae</name> the Epacrideae. See Maroske (2006).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
